  <h2>Why Cabernet Sauvignon Works Best with Steak</h2>

  <p>Cabernet Sauvignon is our sommelier team's top recommendation for steak. The wine's structured tannins cut through the richness of steak, while its dark fruit flavors create a harmonious balance on the palate.</p>

  <h2>Top 3 Wine Styles for Steak</h2>

  <h3>1. Cabernet Sauvignon (Top Pick)</h3>

  <p>Bold and full-bodied, Cabernet Sauvignon brings intensity that stands up to steak's robust flavors.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>**Flavor Profile**: Dark fruits, spice, structured tannins</li>
    <li>**Why It Works**: Tannins cut through fat and protein</li>
    <li>**Price Range**: $15-40</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2. Malbec (Versatile Choice)</h3>

  <p>Malbec offers a more approachable, fruit-forward option that pairs beautifully with a variety of steak preparations.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>**Flavor Profile**: Red fruits, soft tannins, smooth finish</li>
    <li>**Why It Works**: Versatile enough for simple or complex dishes</li>
    <li>**Price Range**: $12-30</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3. Syrah (Budget-Friendly)</h3>

  <p>Don't overlook Syrah as an excellent value option for everyday steak dishes.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>**Flavor Profile**: Earthy, medium-bodied, food-friendly</li>
    <li>**Why It Works**: Great quality-to-price ratio</li>
    <li>**Price Range**: $10-20</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Pairing Tips from Our Sommeliers</h2>

  <h3>Consider the Preparation</h3>

  <p>How your steak is prepared matters as much as the steak itself:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>**Grilled or Roasted**: Go bolder with full-bodied reds</li>
    <li>**Light or Poached**: Choose lighter reds like Pinot Noir</li>
    <li>**With Rich Sauce**: Match the sauce's intensity with your wine choice</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Temperature Matters</h3>

